    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-05-08T22:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-05-08T22:00:00-05:00" n="206"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d206">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 861.00/1758</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in China</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_RPS1"
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Reinsch</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Peking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-05-09T11:00:00+08:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">May 9, 1918, 11 a.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received 11.28 a.m.</hi>]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Your May 6, 6 p.m.<note n="4" xml:id="d206fn4">
                        <hi rend="italic">Ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_153">p. 153</ref>.</note> In
                    accordance with your repeated instructions to keep the Department informed about
                    any developments in Siberia, I allowed <persName corresp="#p_ULA1"
                        >Ustrugov</persName> and <persName>Stal</persName> in two interviews to
                    inform me concerning the plans of the so-called autonomous government of
                    Siberia, reporting to you by mail. <persName corresp="#p_ULA1"
                        >Ustrugov</persName>, who has worked in full harmony with the American
                    Railroad Commission to Russia, was introduced to me by <persName
                        corresp="#p_SJF1">John F. Stevens</persName> and accompanied by
                        <persName>Charles H. Smith</persName>, representing <persName
                        corresp="#p_KAAM1">Admiral Knight</persName>. No observation on their
                    projects was made by me except appreciation of their desire to save Russia for
                    the Allies and a statement that their project would be reported to you, but as
                    long as the government had not established itself on Siberian soil it would be
                    impossible for any power to take <pb facs="0248" n="158" xml:id="pg_158"/> any
                    notice. <persName corresp="#p_KAAV1">Kolchak</persName> and <persName
                        corresp="#p_HGDL1">Horvat</persName> called formally as reported April 30, 2
                        p.m.<note n="1" xml:id="d206fn1">
                        <hi rend="italic">Ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_147">p. 147</ref>.</note>
                    Needless to say no communications of any kind were transmitted for any Russian
                    party by the Legation or received by it.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_RPS1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Reinsch</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
